R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)
##      speed           dist       
##  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
##  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
##  Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
##  Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
##  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
##  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00

Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

library(quantmod)
## Loading required package: xts
## Loading required package: zoo
## 
## Attaching package: 'zoo'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
## Loading required package: TTR
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo
getSymbols("TSLA", from= "2019-11-29")
## [1] "TSLA"
getSymbols("AMZN", from= "2019-11-29")
## [1] "AMZN"
getSymbols("NVDA", from= "2019-11-29")
## [1] "NVDA"
tsla1 <-(TSLA$TSLA.Open)
tsla2 <-(TSLA$TSLA.High)
tsla3 <-(TSLA$TSLA.Close)
amzn1 <-(AMZN$AMZN.Open)
amzn2 <-(AMZN$AMZN.High)
amzn3 <-(AMZN$AMZN.Close)
nvda1 <-(NVDA$NVDA.Open)
nvda2 <-(NVDA$NVDA.High)
nvda3 <-(NVDA$NVDA.Close)
tsla1 <- na.omit(tsla1)
plot(tsla1)

plot(tsla2)

plot(tsla3)

plot(amzn1)

plot(amzn2)

plot(amzn3)

plot(nvda1)

plot(nvda2)

plot(nvda3)

tsla1_dailyreturns<- dailyReturn(tsla1)
tsla1_weeklyreturns<- weeklyReturn(tsla1)
tsla1_monthlyreturns<- monthlyReturn(tsla1)
amzn1_dailyreturns<- dailyReturn(amzn1)
amzn1_weeklyreturns<- weeklyReturn(amzn1)
amzn1_monthlyreturns<- monthlyReturn(amzn1)
nvda1_dailyreturns<- dailyReturn(nvda1)
nvda1_weeklyreturns<- weeklyReturn(nvda1)
nvda1_monthlyreturns<- monthlyReturn(nvda1)
plot(tsla1_dailyreturns)

plot(tsla1, main = "Precios open de TSLA desde 2019")

plot(tsla1_monthlyreturns, main = "Rendimientos Mensuales TSLA desde 2019")

barplot(tsla1_monthlyreturns, main = "Rendimientos Mensuales de TSLA desde 2019 en barras")

barplot(tsla1_weeklyreturns, main = "Rendimientos Semanales de TSLA desde 2019 en barras")

plot_tsla1 <- barplot(na.omit(tsla1_monthlyreturns), main = "Rendimientos Mensuales de Open de TSLA desde 2019")
text(x = plot_tsla1, y = na.omit(tsla1_monthlyreturns) + .09, labels = as.character(round(na.omit(tsla1_monthlyreturns), 4)))

plot_amzn1 <- barplot(na.omit(amzn1_monthlyreturns), main = "Rendimientos Mensuales de Open de AMZN desde 2019")
text(x = plot_amzn1, y = na.omit(amzn1_monthlyreturns) + .09, labels = as.character(round(na.omit(amzn1_monthlyreturns), 4)))

plot_nvda1 <- barplot(na.omit(nvda1_monthlyreturns), main = "Rendimientos Mensuales de Open de NVDA desde 2019")
text(x = plot_nvda1, y = na.omit(nvda1_monthlyreturns) + .09, labels = as.character(round(na.omit(nvda1_monthlyreturns), 4)))
